{"atitle":"sRGB? WUT??","boxes":[{"text":"sRGB is a colorspace generally in use since around 1996.<br><br>If you are unsure what colorspace your texture is, <b>AND</b> its 8 bits/channel, you could assume it is saved in sRGB colorspace.<br>Standard sRGB is 8 bits/channel.<br>There are other colorspaces such as DCI-p3.<br>Sometimes it can be unclear in which colorspace an image is in.<br>For example, HDR ( High Dynamic Range ) usually is in 709/sRGB gamut even though it could be Rec. 2100...<br><br>If you don't modify the colorprofile of an 8 bits/channel such as a .tiff or .jpeg, it will usually be in sRGB colorspace.<br>Generally just assume 8 bit stuff is...<br><br>So why is this important?<br>To quote the VDC :<br><font color=\"#3df40f\">it is probably referring to the differences in colour space values \nbetween the video output of a PC and the Xbox 360, which can result in \nwashed-out/over-saturated colours if not accounted for.\n</font><div id=\"content\" class=\"mw-body\" role=\"main\"><div id=\"bodyContent\" class=\"mw-body-content\"><div id=\"mw-content-text\" dir=\"ltr\" class=\"mw-content-ltr\" lang=\"en\"><div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><font color=\"#3df40f\">It can be ignored unless you're developing for the 360.</font><br></p><p>So yes, if something asks you whether or not your texture is sRGB, just say no and it will be fine.</p><p>This counts both for saving your texture and for importing it, just don't do sRGB and it will be fine.\n</p></div></div></div></div>","contents":[],"border_w":"5px 0px 0px","border_c":"rgb(100, 218, 255) rgb(240, 240, 240) rgb(240, 240, 240)","chapter":""}],"selfid":"4a5af11cd53410d7fdc4b22915f9c71e"}